			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'm not sure about the specifics on Windows, but I think you're confused about something here. You shouldn't have anything time-related in your audio code. The sound hardware keeps its own time, and all you should care about is pumping data into it as fast as it can handle. Buffers should be completely filled and queued for playback as soon as that happens.<br /><br />I need at least three buffers, preferably four, to get decent sound on Linux, but that's partially because it takes way too long to notice when a buffer is ready for more input. I also like to spin a second thread and pump the audio loop at a higher framerate than the video - it cycles at 100 FPS, but will output as much audio as it can, not the same amount each time. This has the added benefit of not stuttering when the framerate gets choppy.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
